<small class="editlink noprint plainlinksneverexpand"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Acids_and_bases&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Acids_and_bases&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow">edit</a></small></div>
<p>An <b>acid</b> (often represented by the generic formula <b>HA</b> [H<sup>+</sup>A<sup>−</sup>]) is traditionally considered any <a href="/wiki/Chemical_compound" title="Chemical compound">chemical compound</a> that, when dissolved in <a href="/wiki/Water" title="Water">water</a>, gives a solution with a <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen_ion" title="Hydrogen ion">hydrogen ion</a> <a href="/wiki/Activity_(chemistry)" title="Activity (chemistry)">activity</a> greater than in pure water, i.e. a <a href="/wiki/PH" title="PH">pH</a> less than 7.0. That approximates the modern definition of <a href="/wiki/Johannes_Nicolaus_Br%C3%B8nsted" title="Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted">Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted</a> and <a href="/wiki/Martin_Lowry" title="Martin Lowry">Martin Lowry</a>, who independently defined an acid as a compound which donates a <a href="/wiki/Hydrogen_ion" title="Hydrogen ion">hydrogen ion</a> (H<sup>+</sup>) to another compound (called a <a href="/wiki/Base_(chemistry)" title="Base (chemistry)">base</a>). Common examples include <a href="/wiki/Acetic_acid" title="Acetic acid">acetic acid</a> (in <a href="/wiki/Vinegar" title="Vinegar">vinegar</a>) and <a href="/wiki/Sulfuric_acid" title="Sulfuric acid">sulfuric acid</a> (used in <a href="/wiki/Car_battery" title="Car battery">car batteries</a>). Acid/base systems are different from <a href="/wiki/Redox" title="Redox">redox</a> reactions in that there is no change in <a href="/wiki/Oxidation_state" title="Oxidation state">oxidation state</a>.</p>
<p>Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be <b>acidic</b> (adjective).</p>
